---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import CommandPager from '../../components/CommandPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'verify';
const description =
  'Bake test, lint, and typecheck commands into context so the agent self-corrects. Pre-commit hook keeps the context honest as the code drifts. The single highest-leverage move in this skill.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="commands">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    If the agent does not have verification commands, <em>you</em> become the
    verification step. That is slow, unreliable, and the root cause of "AI is
    wasting my time". <code>verify</code> makes verification first-class: every
    context file names the commands, a pre-commit hook keeps them in sync, and
    the agent stops shipping you broken diffs to review.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this command exists</h2>
  <p>
    The single biggest difference between teams who feel productive with AI
    and teams who feel like AI is wasting their time is whether the agent has
    rock-solid verification. With it, the agent can iterate locally until
    tests pass; you only review the design. Without it, you are correcting
    typos and missing imports for an hour.
  </p>
  <p>
    The trick is not the commands. The trick is making them <em>visible</em> to
    the agent in the right place. Buried in <code>package.json</code> they are
    technically discoverable; named at the top of <code>CLAUDE.md</code> they
    are inevitable. <code>verify</code> moves them to the top, splits them
    into "fast" (typecheck + lint) and "full" (tests + build), and wires a
    pre-commit hook that fails the commit if <code>CLAUDE.md</code> drifts
    from the code it describes.
  </p>

  <Callout label="Read first" tone="ember">
    <p>
      Verification-driven logic is the fourth
      <a href={url('foundation/cognitive-debt/')}>cognitive debt repayment
      practice</a> and the
      <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>last anti-pattern</a>
      Groundwork rejects (#10, verification as an afterthought). The
      <a href={url('blueprint/#good-practices')}>2026 Blueprint</a> lists it
      among the practices teams must embrace.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>When to reach for it</h2>
  <p>
    Every repo. Every time. This is the single highest-leverage move in this
    skill. If you only run one command after <code>init</code>, run this one.
  </p>
  <p>Specific triggers:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>You just ran <code>init</code> or <code>document</code>. Run <code>verify</code> next.</li>
    <li>Test framework changed.</li>
    <li>New CI pipeline.</li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a> flagged "missing
      verification".
    </li>
    <li>Pre-commit hook drifted (it happens).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What it produces</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Updates to every harness file (<code>CLAUDE.md</code>,
      <code>AGENTS.md</code>, <code>.cursor/rules/main.mdc</code>,
      <code>.github/copilot-instructions.md</code>) with a Verification
      section near the top.
    </li>
    <li>
      <code>.context/hooks/check-context.sh</code>, a pre-commit hook script
      tailored to your stack.
    </li>
    <li>
      Registration with your existing hook runner (husky / pre-commit /
      lefthook) if one is detected. Otherwise, the one-line install
      instruction. Suggest, do not install silently.
    </li>
    <li>
      The Groundwork detector wired in as a pre-commit step and as a CI job
      (<code>.github/workflows/context-check.yml</code> if you use GitHub
      Actions).
    </li>
    <li>
      A short test run of every verification command so you know the baseline
      state.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Detect verification commands.</strong> Reads package manifests
      and build configs to find <code>test</code>, <code>lint</code>,
      <code>typecheck</code>, <code>build</code>, <code>format</code>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Ask which commands are part of the loop.</strong> Detected
      commands are preselected. You adjust. Also asks for the "fast" subset
      (run after every change) vs the "full" set (run before declaring done).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Run each command once.</strong> Confirms it actually works.
      Captures pass / fail. If something is failing, you decide: skip, fix
      now, or include with a "known failing" note.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Update the per-harness files.</strong> The Verification section
      goes near the top of every file. The agent should not have to scroll.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Wire in the detector.</strong>
      <code>npx @ignitic/groundwork detect --fail-on P0</code> in the
      pre-commit hook and in CI. Ten deterministic rules. No LLM.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Install the local drift hook.</strong> Checks repo-specific
      cross-file invariants: did <code>package.json</code> change but
      <code>CLAUDE.md</code> still name the old package manager? Did
      <code>.context/conventions.md</code> change without regenerating the
      per-harness files?
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Register the hook</strong> with your hook runner if one exists.
      Otherwise tell you the one-line install command.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <Callout label="Fast vs full" tone="mute">
    <p>
      The split matters. If the only option is "run the full suite", agents
      run it once, then never again. Give them a fast loop they can hit after
      every meaningful step, and a full loop they hit before declaring done.
      Most projects: fast = typecheck + lint, full = all four.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2>Failure modes the command guards against</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Listing commands that do not work.</strong> Run them. If a
      command does not work in this repo, do not write it into context.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Hook that always passes.</strong> Pointless. Remove or make it
      actually check something.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Hook that fails on legitimate changes.</strong> Worse than no
      hook. Test on a sample change before declaring done.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>No fast / full split.</strong> Agents will run the full suite
      once and then never again. Give them a fast loop.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Related ideas</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/cognitive-debt/')}>Cognitive debt</a>.
      Verification-first is the fourth repayment practice.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/anti-patterns/')}>Anti-patterns</a> #10:
      verification as an afterthought.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('foundation/contextops-lifecycle/')}>ContextOps lifecycle</a>.
      Maintain stage. Hooks and CI checks live here.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#good-practices')}>2026 Blueprint:
      verification-driven logic</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <CommandPager slug="verify" />
</Doc>
